After reading about Kevin's fantastic project to turn a cheap Lattice FPGA development board into a fully functional logic analyzer (https://blackmesalabs.wordpress.com/2016/10/24/sump2-96-msps-logic-analyzer-for-22/) I couldn't resist ordering one and building a logic analyzer myself.

Once I had everything up and running (with Kevin's fantastic support) I decided it was missing a case, so here you will find the results of that case design.

It isn't fantastic, but if you find it useful, great.

I designed this in OpenSCAD but have also included the STL file for folks who don't have OpenSCAD installed.

There are a few parameters which can be changed if your board doesn't quite fit, or if you would prefer thicker/thinner walls, more overlap between top and bottom, a different top/bottom split point etc... so play around.

While working on my sand trooper costume, I found the lack of available print files frustrating. I'm a novice at modeling, so there is probably a lot of dumb in here, but it seems to be a decent base.

Assembled_radio_face is the whole front panel with buttons. I don't really recommend printing this, but it's there if you want it.

Radio face and radio back are the main parts of the radio. I print those at 0.2mm layer height, then print the buttons separately on my SLA printer (or at least at 0.1mm on the FDM).

Update 7 Dec. 2016: "Top right knob" replaced with new version

Printer:

Folgertech TF5

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

see below

Notes:

This is modeled for a large format printer. If your print bed is less than 12x12, you'll have to cut the file up with netfab/meshimixer/whatever tool you like.

I printed the face and back at 0.2mm layer height, 80mm/s, and the buttons at 0.1mm height, 60mm/s (with outlines slowed to 60% speed in simplify 3d). The result is a print that wasn't a lot of work to clean up nice and smooth.

Cleanup

You'll need to smooth the print lines out. In my opinion it's too much detail to use an epoxy coat, so I think sanding + glazing putty is the way to go.

Designed in Onshape

I gathered what reference images of the real radios I could find and did my best on measurements. I see some flaws in there, but nothing big enough to be worth the effort to correct right now.

description.text:
I have a Kenmore 183.94679 (equiv 183.94673); the thermostat died and it wouldn't turn off the compressor (even when set to off) - everything froze. While Sears is very good about selling replacement parts (http://www.searspartsdirect.com/model-number/18/394673/0582/0163200.html), the thermostat (Parts #: RF-7350-124) is no longer available. Someone else had had this problem and talked with Haier to find out the RF-7350-101 would work. However, when I received it, it wouldn't mount to the fridge and didn't come with any of its own mounting hardware.

This little mount fixes that problem. First, there is a small pin on the thermostat than must be bent flush (careful, this is not the on/off switch - that also sticks out; the pin is part of the chasis). I printed the mount in PLA, 100% in-fill. I then used a M10 1.25 tap to thread the center hole (not strictly necessary, but minimizes potential cracking); then put the existing metal plate over the thermostat and screw the mount on. I used the existing mount screws + two #8-32 nuts to secure the mount to the metal plate (not strictly necessary, but minimizes slippage).

Then install as normal. I don't normally have to change the thermostat setting, so I'm not entirely sure how long this would last if you had to turn it a lot, but so far it's done the trick.

I've included the Inventor file if you need to adjust for a different model thermostat.

I am printing these items currently for final testing.

This is a variation on Cruzher's awesome design! I wanted a way to make multiple organizers stackable or connectable. So I added an "X" slot to the tops and bottoms in all 4 corners. I have included a new Cube with the "X" connector slots included in the .STL file.

If you place 2 of these next to each other and print the short X connector it will attach them as a single unit. You can even attach the top of one to the bottom of another to make these very secure in a stacked formation.


The list of connectors so far are:
  • 1.5mm X connector for side by side connections
  • 1.5mm Half-X connector for filling the blank spots if you like
  • 3mm X connector for side by side with stacked cubes
  • 3mm Half-X for direct top to bottom stacked cubes
  • 3mm Split-Half-X for offset top to bottom stacked cubes
  • Tall 113.5mm X leg for free standing cube to desktop
  • Tall 113.5mm Half-X leg for free standing cube to desktop
  • Tall 115mm X leg for for stacking cubes
  • Tall 115mm Half-X leg for for stacking cubes

Mixing various configurations can provide some neat solutions for any desk!
The files are free to use and modify - but please remember Cruzher made this organizer I only added a feature to an already great design!

description.text: Inspired by Prusa i3 idler. This is a match for my internal motor mount (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:186076) and belt mount (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:41571). All together they make a completely internal Y-axis. See instructions for assembly and hardware required. Once assembled you can tighten the belt just by turning the adjustment screw clockwise, up to ~15 mm of adjustment possible. Note: I have a sized up machine with a sized up bed, this works fine for me and does not limit bed motion. Please double check before installing on your machine. Ignore the messy wiring in all my pictures, I'm in the process of a major printer re-work. Update: Added Sketchup source file

Hardware required: 1x M5 30mm + Nut
1x M4 25mm + Nut and Washer
1x M8 25mm + Nut
1x 608zz bearing 2x M5 10mm for mounting to frame
  • Place the M4 and M5 nuts in appropriate nut traps (M5 mates with long groove and M4 is the adjusting screw).
  • Place in the bearing and secure with M8 screw.
  • Connect the two pieces together with the M5 screw, it should fit snuggly in the long groove but not be too tight to move.
  • Put the M4 adjusting screw through both pieces, the starting position should be with the block as far out as possible.
  • Mount onto frame of printer and tighten belt by hand, one belt is secure additional tightening is available by turning the M4 screw clockwise.

comments.text: Ok, if you look at the first picture, the idler starts with the M4 being loose, just so it is threaded through the captive M4 nut.  Then the belt is threaded around the idler, pulled finger tight and secured to the carriage.  At this point there should already be some tension in the belt, to increase the tension in the belt you begin to turn the M4 screw clockwise which pulls against the belt thus making it tighter.

This thing mounts Simple & Smart Spool Holder right on top of the Anet A8 printer. The result is a very compact and easy to change spool holder. Included filament guide prevents the filament from falling off the spool.

After consulting some math teachers, they told me that teaching the cartesian plane is difficult to do with all three axes. A whiteboard or chalkboard cannot show the Z axis. Print "Cartesian Plane Face" twice using the MakerWare slicing profile provided. Simply slide the two together at the notch.  
Print "3 Axis Corner" once with the same slicing profile to use as a moveable Z-axis.  
Natural PLA is recommended however any translucent filament should work.

description.text: A connector to join a dust bag to a DeWalt Mitre saw.

One of my friends asked if I could make him an adapter for his Dewalt mitre saw.. He bought a dust collecting bag off E-Bay and the exhaust outlet pipe and dust bag inlet pipe where the same  diameter. Well he measured it at 1.522â and 1.527â respectively., I think they were the same but, here is the result. One was designed in TinkerCad and the other in OpenSCAD. I wasnât happy with the Tinkercad versions as I couldnât seem to get the centers of the cylinders to line up and consequently the internal diameter is off center. I need to spend more time using it I think,  as I was rushing to get it done before dinner.  Also I wanted to try using OpenSCAD. Both files are listed. I created a ridge in the middle of the connector that differentiates the two different diameters. I used Makerware to put both pipes on the print bed. I used the defaults on Makerware for my Replicator 1 with the exception off increasing the HBP to 120F. It took just about 4 hours to print. The "Pumo" is a very traditional artifact from south italy, Apulia, where it can be spotted on balconies of houses.

The handmade ceramic "Pumo" is the result of an ancient manual tradition and holds a precious message: it represents a rose bud that's about to blossom surrounded by three acanthus leaves that symbolize spring, rebirth, life and renewal. In addition to being an amulet for luck, abundance, prosperity, fertility and good news it is also a decorative artifact that captivates with its rounded shape and its colorful glazing.

The "Pumo" adapts to celebrate all the occasions you want to wish a good start for.

I found out that the term derives from the Latin pomum, "fruit", and is linked to the cult of the Roman goddess Pomona, who was the protectress of the fruits. In some Apulian dialects the "Pumo" is called "Pumo dè Fiure" (flower bud) and was also used in many coat-of-arms of the Apulian upper-class families. It is also believed to keep away the evil. This is why you can see the "Pumos" at the entrance of the traditional houses or on the facades of the mansions .

You can find more info on google by searching "pumo di ceramica"

UPDATE! I've udated the system A LOT! now has rate presets, as well as plastic editing by form! To use it, open the spreadsheet and ALLOW MACROS (they're needed to make the application work) Then go to the "Plastics Available" tab and enter the plastics you have, and their respective prices per kilogram. Next, Go to the "Rates" sheet and enter the price you charge per hour for your time, and the machine's time. Then enter how much profit over the original part you wish to make, finally, enter the percentage of each print you spend "babysitting" the machine. Once all this is done, the application is ready to use! Return to the "Jobs" sheet and press "Calculate another print" in the top left corner. Enter the information about the print, and press ok! The program will then do all the necesary math, and as long as the values in the "plastic" and "rates" sheets are in the correct format (NUMBERS ONLY) it will return a price!

description.text:
X-axis, hotendholder and fanduct (Remix by "muvid") are remix´s of toolson´s MK2 P3Steel --> www.scheuten.me

Printsize on X with a Graber i3 is 198mm.

Note:

The parts are not professionally drawn. All parts were created by "copy & paste" via tinkercad. Certain inaccuracies also, but it works great :o).

Required parts for the X axis:

4x MF126 bearing
1x 608Z bearing
2x headless screw M4x25
M3, M4, M6 screws & nuts
2x Hall Endstops & magnet

Required parts for the direktextruder:

Hobb-Goblin von E3D
bearing 624-2Z
Spring
2x Fan https://www.digikey.de/product-detail/de/delta-electronics/BFB03512HHA-AF00/603-1361-ND/2560485 or any other 35x35x10 radialfan
M3 & M4 screws and nuts.

The extruder files must be mirrored befor printing for the right Extruder.

description.text: Teach students about graphing coordinates using this game inspired by battleship.

Students will work individually or in pairs against one other team to be the first to guess the coordinates of each of the other team's shapes. Students may find it helpful to have two boards per team one to record their guesses and one with their shapes which also records the other team's hits and misses. To start:
  • Students will place the shapes anywhere on their game board. The shapes may not be stacked.
  • Students take turns guessing coordinates.
  • After each guess, the opposing team will declare if the guess was a hit or a miss and then take their own turn.
  • When one team has hit all the points in one shape they should be told that the shape has been completely "hit" and play continues.
  • The game is over when one team has hit all of the other team's shapes completely.
    • *For more advanced math classes students should guess lines using standard or slope-intercept form and mark these using rubberbands stretched between two pegs.

description.text:
The skis are a direct fit onto the undercarriage legs of the Durafly Tundra RC plane. Remove the original wheels, slide the skis into place and add a collet on the axle to stop them coming off. A rubber band is used to hold the ski tips high, looped around the forward hook, around the undercarriage leg and back to the hook. This allows them to lie flat under the weight of the model and give them movement over rougher snow terrain. Experimenting will be necessary get the correct tension of rubber band. The ski has an axle hole of close to the correct size but this will need cleaning out with a suitable drill bit before fitting. The forward hook has a support built in which will need cutting to allow the hook to be used. It has a slot for the upright part of undercarriage leg, allowing forward and backward movement making the skis right and left handed.
The right hand ski
The ski was drawn up in Fusion 360 as a right hand version. As fusion 360 outputs a .stl file on its side I then load the file into Cura to turn it 90 degrees to lie flat then turning 90 degrees around to get the length of the ski on the Y axis. It just fits my 3D printer this way.
The printer is set up for a layer height of 0.2mm with 100% fill. It may be possible to have a lower fill, maybe 75% or less but I wanted a solid ski.
The left hand ski
In Cura, with the length of the ski on the Y axis a simple mirror flip of the X axis produces the left ski.
The curved front
With a pair of flat skis produced the next step is to curve the front of both of them upwards.
I cut a suitably sized block of wood to a ski shape then carefully heated the front of the ski with a heat gun (the sort used for shrinking iron on covering for models). It softens easily and can be pressed into shape on the wooden former, once it has cooled the ski is complete. You might manage without a former but it is easier to get identical shapes with one.
Roll on the snowy weather :o)

Update 28/2/17
I had a request to spilt the ski so it could be printed on a smaller bed printer so I've done this and added a central 6mm hole and two 1.5mm holes so when glued together a 6mm central dowel of wood, carbon, ali etc. could be glued in to strengthen it along with maybe 1.5mm carbon or piano wire on the outer edges. The holes will probably need drilling out to the correct diameter once printed. I use a solvent glue for PLA quite successfully (Solvent Weld Cement available from model shops in UK) Again as above you will need to produce a left and tight hand version. This latest addition HAS NOT been test printed as yet so if you try it let me know how it works.

comments.text: You've designed the best stuff. I flew off skis the first time this winter (2016-2017). It is a misperception that one can fly off deep, soft snow with skis. The distribution of weight is too high on the skis and the plane sinks in untl the prop is running in the snow. I had to blast away the foot of snow to get down to just a 1" to 2" skim of snow, then all was great. So far, we haven't had snow this season that got a crust on top - the other alternative. My other realization is that trike-geared planes will get the nose gear beaten to smithereens - very rough on the nose gear set up. I am converting a .40 size trainer to taildragger just to have the skis work great. The big point is that it doesn't seem you need too big of ski as you will really only be flying from a thin skim of snow or a crusty or packed surface. Flying off skis and figuring this stuff out was great fun this winter - as if the season never slowed down.

The second two images show the same angle a but using the blue tape mark at 8 there can be two different triangles with the same angle a and length A.
